{"id":"1809.07046","submitter":"Xiangyun Tang","authors":"Liehuang Zhu, Xiangyun Tang, Meng Shen, Xiaojiang Du, Mohsen Guizani","title":"Privacy-Preserving DDoS Attack Detection Using Cross-Domain Traffic in\n  Software Defined Networks","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.NI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Existing distributed denial-of-service attack detection in software defined\nnetworks (SDNs) typically perform detection in a single domain. In reality,\nabnormal traffic usually affects multiple network domains. Thus, a cross-domain\nattack detection has been proposed to improve detection performance. However,\nwhen participating in detection, the domain of each SDN needs to provide a\nlarge amount of real traffic data, from which private information may be\nleaked. Existing multiparty privacy protection schemes often achieve privacy\nguarantees by sacrificing accuracy or increasing the time cost. Achieving both\nhigh accuracy and reasonable time consumption is a challenging task. In this\npaper, we propose Predis, which is a privacypreserving cross-domain attack\ndetection scheme for SDNs. Predis combines perturbation encryption and data\nencryption to protect privacy and employs a computationally simple and\nefficient algorithm k-Nearest Neighbors (kNN) as its detection algorithm. We\nalso improve kNN to achieve better efficiency. Via theoretical analysis and\nextensive simulations, we demonstrate that Predis is capable of achieving\nefficient and accurate attack detection while securing sensitive information of\neach domain.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Sep 2018 07:56:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-09-20"}
{"id":"1809.07047","submitter":"Masato Ito","authors":"Masato Ito","title":"Lambert W function and hanging chain revisited","comments":"11 pages, 6 figures, v2: comments added, misprints corrected, v3:\n  corrected some typos","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"AUE 18-01","categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In classical physics, calculating the slack of a hanging chain is a problem\nthat has attracted interest. This study aims to solve this problem through\nexperiment and theory. When the length and distance of both the ends of a\nhanging chain are given, the length of slack can be expressed by a Lambert W\nfunction or an irrational function within a certain distance. Herein, a simple\nobservation of the slack is presented. The result obtained is one of the\napplications of the Lambert W function in the field of physics. Though the\nshape of a hanging chain is well-known to be a catenary, the calculation of\nslack possesses richer aspects of mathematical physics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Sep 2018 07:57:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 29 Sep 2018 12:11:46 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 18 Jan 2019 23:06:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-01-23"}
